<article id="post-708" class="post-708 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-student-focus tag-arts">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/what-do-bassoons-and-biology-have-in-common/" rel="bookmark">What Do Bassoons and Biology Have in Common?</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/what-do-bassoons-and-biology-have-in-common/" title="Permalink to What Do Bassoons and Biology Have in Common?" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T21:02:27+00:00">May 5, 2014</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-02-15T18:11:52+00:00">February 15, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div>
<div>
<p>On the surface bassoons and biology don’t seem to go together, but that doesn’t bother Philip Schorsch. The sophomore biology major has played the bassoon for three years now and is a member of the UIC Concert Band. His favorite part of being a band member is observing how all the different instruments compliment each other to create beautiful music. Schorsch’s love for observing how complex, complete processes are derived from smaller, simple pieces also explains his passion for biology: “I like the complexity and the fact [that] it’s about life.”</p>
<div id="attachment_709" style="width: 210px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.02.59-PM.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-709" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-9.02.59-PM.png" alt="Philip Schorsch, a member of the UIC Concert Band, pictured with his bassoon" width="200" height="300" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Philip Schorsch, a member of the UIC Concert Band, pictured with his bassoon</p></div>
<p>In addition to being a member of the UIC Concert Band, Schorsch is actively involved in the Honors College. As an Honors Ambassador he is an extra resource for first-year students, serving as a mentor and lending his trained ears for when they have questions. “When you’re in band, you have to pay particular attention to other instruments,” Schorsch continues, “[That idea] transfers over to listening to other people.”</p>
</div>
<div>
<p>In addition to honing his leadership skills, being at the Honors College has provided him with opportunities he knows he wouldn’t find anywhere else. “At UIC, the class sizes are really big and [students sometimes aren’t able to connect frequently with their professors], so you get a better sense of community in the Honors College.”</p>
<p>However, balancing the time commitments of playing an instrument and being an Ambassador can be tough; Schorsch makes schedules in order to maintain focus. He’s planning to go through the pre-pharmacy track in preparation for pharmacy school and is also considering assisting his fellow, Dr. Seungpyo Hong, with research in biopharmaceuticals. But he has no plans to set down the bassoon any time soon. Schorsch is looking forward to more musical opportunities at UIC as he continues his studies in the field of life.</p>
<p><em>by: Renee Ronzone, Junior, Anthropology</em></p>
</div>
</div>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-703" class="post-703 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-student-focus tag-arts tag-capstone tag-research-2">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/capstone-focus-a-dimensional-end-to-senior-year/" rel="bookmark">Capstone Focus: A Dimensional End to Senior Year</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/capstone-focus-a-dimensional-end-to-senior-year/" title="Permalink to Capstone Focus: A Dimensional End to Senior Year" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2014-05-05T20:41:31+00:00">May 5, 2014</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-02-15T18:12:25+00:00">February 15, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<div>
<div>
<div>
<div id="attachment_704" style="width: 160px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-8.42.19-PM.png"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-704" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Screen-Shot-2014-06-25-at-8.42.19-PM.png" alt="Melissa Romeo" width="150" height="150" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Melissa Romeo</p></div>
<p>For UIC senior Melissa Romeo, the Honors Capstone project is more than just an assignment. Romeo—who is majoring in art history with a minor in psychology—is situating her Capstone project as the basis for future exploration.</p>
<p>The Art History course AH 160: “Trends in International Contemporary Art Since 1960” inspired her to formulate her project around Andrea Fraser, a performance artist who created pieces that analyze the intimate physical relationships among humans. In engaging with Fraser’s work, Romeo decided to use psychoanalysis to examine the dichotomy between expectations of the emotions involved in physical relationship and the reality of today’s society. As a result, Romeo has begun to see art as an incorporation of many fields that go far beyond what meets the eye.</p>
<p>Romeo’s Capstone represents “personal progression” and a contemporary twist on her passion for Italian Renaissance Art.</p>
</div>
<div>
<p>Her project presently consists of conducting research on Fraser as Romeo attempts to determine whether the artist explores questions of physical alienation or hope resulting from societal expectations of physical relationships. Romeo thanks her Fellow Professor Hannah Higgins, her Capstone Supervisor Dr. Elise Archias, and the Honors College for assisting her throughout the development of her Capstone. Both her Supervisor and her Fellow helped Romeo select her Capstone topic and continue to support her by giving her feedback every step of the way. They make sure that her project has a concrete focus, and ultimately have helped her make it her own.</p>
<p>Romeo is currently working at an art gallery—which has also influenced her Capstone project—and she hopes to establish a career in art therapy. Romeo wants to have an impact on other students before she leaves UIC and encourages them to use their Capstone projects as a springboard, one that is “ongoing, accelerated, [and] forever expanding [an] idea that may someday become their life.”</p>
<p><em>by: Sanjana Anil, Freshman, Biological Sciences and Communication</em></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-503" class="post-503 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-events tag-arts tag-chicago tag-chicago-signature-honors-programming">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/chicago-signature-programming/" rel="bookmark">The Honors College Explores: Chicago Signature Programming</a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/chicago-signature-programming/" title="Permalink to The Honors College Explores: Chicago Signature Programming" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2013-11-17T22:39:38+00:00">November 17, 2013</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-02-16T21:03:52+00:00">February 16, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/rpate243/" title="View all posts by rpate243">rpate243</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<p>While it is well known that Honors College students stay busy in the classroom, there are<br />
also many ways for them to broaden their horizons outside of their daily course schedules. The<br />
Honors College’s Chicago Signature Honors Programming offers students valuable opportunities<br />
to explore the rich variety of cultural and educational attractions in Chicago. Under the guidance<br />
of Post-Doctoral Fellows in Teaching and Mentoring Dr. Vernon Lindsay and Dr. Aleks<br />
Zarnitsyn, students can take advantage of discounted or free tickets provided by the Honors<br />
College to attend performances at the Lyric Opera, the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, the<br />
Steppenwolf Theatre Company, and other distinguished art sites across the city. Students may<br />
also explore cultural centers such as Chinatown or visit a variety of museums throughout the<br />
diverse urban environment.</p>
<p>Since the fall semester began, Chicago Signature Honors Programming has already<br />
hosted a number of excursions, including the Soviet film Nostalghia at the Gene Siskel Center,<br />
the Verdi’s opera Otello (based on the Shakespeare play Othello) at the Lyric Opera of Chicago,<br />
and the American drama This Is Our Youth at the Prop Theatre. Students are often given the<br />
opportunity to participate in group reflections or speak with the actors, directors, or artists behind<br />
the scenes, making the experience even more meaningful.<br />
One excursion, the trip to see the Broadway musical The Color Purple at the Mercury<br />
Theater Chicago, was particularly memorable for sophomore Monica Makar. “I don’t usually<br />
enjoy musicals at all, but that was truly phenomenal,” Makar proclaimed. “I was so impressed<br />
with how they translated such a difficult, serious novel into a moving show that made me want to<br />
both laugh and cry.”<br />
Chicago Signature Honors Programming has only just begun for the year, and upcoming<br />
outings include a trip to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra as well as the Art Institute of Chicago.<br />
Students are encouraged to reserve their spots early online in order to participate in the vast<br />
amount of exciting events to come!<br />
By: Sarah Lee &#8211; Sophomore – Biochemistry</p>
<p><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Honors-College-students-take-a-trip-to-see-The-Color-Purple.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-504" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Honors-College-students-take-a-trip-to-see-The-Color-Purple.jpg" alt="Honors College students take a trip to see The Color Purple" width="665" height="498" /></a></p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
			
		
